Paper 1

RF Fundamentals: Q Factor & Chu Limit

What is Quality Factor (Q)?

Q measures how much energy an antenna stores vs how much it radiates:

\(Q = \frac{f_0}{BW} = 2\pi \cdot \frac{E_{stored}}{E_{lost/cycle}}\)
fâ‚€ center frequency (Hz) â€“ where antenna works best
BW Bandwidth â€“ the range of frequencies the antenna covers. Example: 100 MHz BW at 1 GHz center = works from 950-1050 MHz
Q Type Real-World Example
~5-15 Low Q UWB antenna (3-10 GHz)
~20-50 Medium WiFi patch antenna (2.4 GHz)
~50-100 High Q ESA in smartphone (narrow BW)

What is the Chu Limit?

The Chu Limit (1948) is a physics law that says: for any antenna of size ka, there is a minimum Q (maximum bandwidth) it can ever achieve:

\(Q_{min} \geq \frac{1}{(ka)^3} + \frac{1}{ka}\)

This comes directly from Maxwell's equations. No matter how clever your design, you cannot beat this limit.

If ka = Then Q â‰¥ Max BW â‰¤
0.3 (tiny) ~40 2.5%
0.5 ~10 10%
0.8 (larger) ~3.5 30%

ğŸ’¡ How This Paper Uses the Chu Limit

Traditional: make antenna â†’ simulate â†’ check. This paper's innovation: Use Chu limit during optimization as a guide. Only search in the achievable region below the limit.

Paper 1

The ESA Bandwidth Problem

What is "Electrically Small"?

An antenna is electrically small when its size is much smaller than the radio wave it transmits.

\(ka = \frac{2\pi \cdot f \cdot a}{c}\)
k wavenumber = 2Ï€/Î» (how many radians per meter)
a antenna radius (meters)
f frequency (Hz) â€“ how many cycles per second
c speed of light = 3Ã—10â¸ m/s
Ï€ pi â‰ˆ 3.14159
When ka < 0.5
â†’ Antenna is "Electrically Small"

WHY Small = Narrow Bandwidth?

Here's the physics step-by-step:

Step 1: Why do small antennas store energy?

â†’ Small antennas can't radiate efficiently. The wave doesn't "detach" cleanlyâ€”energy builds up around the antenna like water pressure behind a small pipe.

Step 2: What is "near-field"? (Wheeler's Radiansphere)

â†’ Harold Wheeler (1947) defined the radiansphere: a sphere of radius Î»/2Ï€ around the antenna. Inside this region, fields store energy instead of radiating. Small antennas (ka < 0.5) are entirely within their own radiansphere!

Step 3: Why High stored energy = High Q?

â†’ Q = (Energy Stored) / (Energy Radiated per cycle). More storage = higher Q. (You learned about Q on the previous slide!)

Step 4: Why High Q = Narrow Bandwidth?

â†’ High Q means the antenna is very "picky" about frequency (like a tuning fork). It only works well at one exact frequency.

âš ï¸ This is physics, not poor engineering! Maxwell's equations guarantee that small antennas must store energy.

Paper 2

The FSS Inverse Design Problem

FSS Unit Cell Structure

Periodic metallic patterns with 3 domains that filter EM waves

What is a Frequency Selective Surface?

A periodic array of metallic patterns on a substrate that filters EM waves by frequency.

Acts like an optical filter, but for radio waves

  • Radomes - protect radar while passing signals
  • EMI shielding - block unwanted frequencies
  • 5G/6G - smart surfaces for wireless

The Inverse Design Challenge

Forward: Given geometry â†’ compute S21 (transmission response) âœ“ (easy)

Inverse: Given desired S21 â†’ find geometry âœ— (HARD!)

Traditional approach:

  • Generate 100,000+ random geometries
  • Simulate each â†’ months of computation!

ğŸ’¡ Solution: Use physics in neural network loss!

RF Fundamentals: FSS Structure & Mode Matching

FSS Structure (from Paper)

Fig. 1: FSS unit cell in infinite arrays with 3 domains

Shape function: g(x,y) = 0 (metal) or 1 (aperture)

Floquet Mode Expansion

For periodic structures, fields expand as:

\(E(x,y,z) = \sum_{mn} C_{mn} Î¦_{mn}(x,y) e^{-jÎ²_{mn} z}\)
C_mn Mode coefficients (solve for these)
Î²_mn Propagation constant per mode
Î¦_mn Spatial mode pattern

Mode Matching Method

100-1000x faster than FDTD/FEM:

  • Divide into regions
  • Expand E, H as mode series
  • Match tangential fields at interfaces
  • Solve linear system â†’ S-params

Paper 3

The 6G Real-Time Control Problem

6G and mmWave Challenges

6G will use mmWave (30-300 GHz) and THz bands for massive bandwidth. But there's a catch:

  • High path loss: Signal weakens quickly with distance
  • Blockage: Human bodies, walls block signal completely
  • Narrow beams: Must aim precisely at each user

Solution: Reconfigurable Intelligent Surfaces (RIS)

ğŸ’¡ mmWave = flashlight (bright but narrow). RIS = "smart mirror" to redirect around obstacles.

The Control Problem

A typical RIS has 256+ phase-shifting elements. Each must be set optimally:

Challenge:

  • 256 elements Ã— 2Ï€ phase = huge search space
  • Channel changes every few ms
  • Traditional optimization: ~100ms per update
  • Required: <1ms for real-time

Need 100x speedup for practical 6G!

RF Fundamentals: RIS, Beamforming, SINR

RIS Structure (from Paper)

  • Each element: patch + varactor
  • Varactor bias â†’ phase shift (0-2Ï€)
  • Low power vs. active relays

Beamforming

Steer RF beam by controlling phase:

\(\theta = \arcsin\left(\frac{\Delta\phi \lambda}{2\pi d}\right)\)

Phase difference â†’ beam direction

RIS adds reflective beamforming on top of transmit beamforming.

Sum-Rate Objective

Maximize total data rate for all users:

\(R = \sum_k \log_2(1 + \text{SINR}_k)\)

SINR = Signal / (Interference + Noise)

Balance: helping one user may interfere with others!

ğŸ’¡ Three pillars of 6G: RIS hardware + Beamforming physics + System optimization â†’ Connected via LLM

How RIMSA Works

Now that you understand RIS hardware, let's see why Paper 3's approach (RIMSA) is superior to traditional RIS (DMA).

Old: Serial Feed (DMA)

Watch the circles do "the wave" (like fans in a stadium)

âš ï¸ Three Critical Problems:

  • Beam Squint: Different frequencies arrive at different times â†’ beam spreads like a rainbow â†’ user can't catch full signal
  • Intersymbol Interference: First element sends new bit while last element still sends old bit â†’ air fills with mixed 1s and 0s â†’ data corruption
  • Narrowband Only: Forced to use slow signals to avoid problems #1 and #2

New: Parallel Feed (RIMSA)

Watch the circles "breathe together"

âœ“ What RIMSA Solves:

  • Independent Control: Phase and Amplitude adjust separately (no coupling)
  • Direct Transmission: Signal generated on surface â†’ no double fading â†’ high gain

âš ï¸ New Problem Created:

  • Control Complexity: 1000s of independent knobs â†’ LLM solves this in real-time
